  abstract = {We establish an improved classical algorithm for solving linear systems in a model analogous to the QRAM that is used by quantum linear solvers. Precisely, for the linear system \$A\textbackslash x = \textbackslash b\$, we show that there is a classical algorithm that outputs a data structure for \$\textbackslash x\$ allowing sampling and querying to the entries, where \$\textbackslash x\$ is such that \$\textbackslash |\textbackslash x - A\^\{-1\}\textbackslash b\textbackslash |\textbackslash leq \textbackslash epsilon \textbackslash |A\^\{-1\}\textbackslash b\textbackslash |\$. This output can be viewed as a classical analogue to the output of quantum linear solvers. The complexity of our algorithm is \$\textbackslash widetilde\{O\}(\textbackslash kappa\_F\^6 \textbackslash kappa\^2/\textbackslash epsilon\^2 )\$, where \$\textbackslash kappa\_F = \textbackslash |A\textbackslash |\_F\textbackslash |A\^\{-1\}\textbackslash |\$ and \$\textbackslash kappa = \textbackslash |A\textbackslash |\textbackslash |A\^\{-1\}\textbackslash |\$. This improves the previous best algorithm [Gily\{\textbackslash 'e\}n, Song and Tang, arXiv:2009.07268] of complexity \$\textbackslash widetilde\{O\}(\textbackslash kappa\_F\^6 \textbackslash kappa\^6/\textbackslash epsilon\^4)\$. Our algorithm is based on the randomized Kaczmarz method, which is a particular case of stochastic gradient descent. We also find that when \$A\$ is row sparse, this method already returns an approximate solution \$\textbackslash x\$ in time \$\textbackslash widetilde\{O\}(\textbackslash kappa\_F\^2)\$, while the best quantum algorithm known returns \$\textbackslash ket\{\textbackslash x\}\$ in time \$\textbackslash widetilde\{O\}(\textbackslash kappa\_F)\$ when \$A\$ is stored in the QRAM data structure. As a result, assuming access to QRAM and if \$A\$ is row sparse, the speedup based on current quantum algorithms is quadratic.},
